jury selection began today in a civil trial 
arising from the 1983 korean air lines disaster in which a jumbo jet 
strayed into soviet air space and was shot down by a soviet fighter 
plane killing all 269 people aboard 
families of passengers killed in the shootdown of flight 007 are 
seeking to prove in court that the airliners crew engaged in 
willful misconduct 
the international civil aviation organization concluded flight 
007 had been off course for nearly 5 hours before it was destroyed 
us district court judge aubrey robinson is presiding at the 
civil trial which he told a pool of 36 prospective jurors will last 
three to four weeks a sixmember jury and three alternates are to 
be chosen from the pool of district of columbia residents 
lawyers for the families said they expect to present about 10 
witnesses several of them korean air lines crew members who flew 
the northern pacific route of the illfated flight 007 lawyers for 
the airline said they may present nearly two dozen witnesses 
including as many as 11 employees of the federal aviation 
administration 
lawyers for the families suggest in court papers that crew 
members aboard the boeing 747 knew shortly after leaving anchorage 
alaska on the last leg of their journey that because of an error 
they made before takeoff they were operating without a reliable 
inertia navigation system the three computerized devices aboard the 
aircraft were the primary means of navigating the flight 
instead of temporarily aborting the flight to reprogram the 
system the crew may have decided to navigate the flight without it 
in clear violation of proper piloting procedure say the families 
lawyers 
crewmen aboard some previous flights that had been aborted had 
been disciplined 
the plaintiffs contend that willful misconduct by the jets crew 
makes the airline liable for damages in excess of the 
75000perpassenger limit normally permitted under international 
agreement 
the us government said the plane was lost due to a navigational 
mistake and that its pilot did not know he was over soviet 
territory the soviet union contends the plane intentionally flew 
its course to photograph sensitive military installations 
the jumbo jet was flying from new york to seoul south korea 
when a soviet military jet attacked it over sakhalin island a site 
of soviet military installations 
rep larry mcdonald dga who was the chairman of the john 
birch society and 60 other us citizens were among the victims 
kal says the only inference that can be drawn from the assumed 
deviation from a normal flight path is that the crew was negligent 
in failing to notice it had gone off course the judge said in a 
ruling last november that negligence may not be the only explanation 
a failure to notice that the flight was offcourse at point a 
or point b or point c might be evidence only of negligence 
said robinson but a failure to notice that the flight was 
offcourse at point a and point b and point c is susceptible to 
a different interpretation 
that different interpretation is that the crew was aware of 
its deviation but elected not to report it and take corrective 
action suggested the judge 
robinson found sufficient evidence for a conclusion that the crew 
of flight 007 knew the navigation system aboard the plane was 
unreliable 
