<TEXT>
the nations main weather satellite has moved 
to its summer home better to watch for hurricanes threatening the 
east and gulf coasts the national oceanic and atmospheric 
administration said monday 
the selfpropelled satellite has moved to a position over the 
equator at 98 degrees west longitude nearly due south of central 
texas the satellite has been located at 108 degrees west longitude 
due south of western new mexico 
the move means the satellite will be able to see 690 miles 
farther east in the atlantic ocean to give warning of tropical 
storms developing off the coast of africa 
normally the national environmental satellite data and 
information service operates two stationary weather satellites at 
22300 miles altitude over the equator but one of them failed last 
january it will be replaced next year 
in the meantime the lone stationary satellite is moved west in 
the winter to watch out for storms developing in the pacific ocean 
and east in summer to help track developing hurricanes 
</TEXT>
