<TEXT>
the war on cancer has brought improved 
therapies for americas middle class and affluent but the disease is 
too often a needless death sentence for the poor the american 
cancer society president said monday 
for the 37 million americans who do not have health insurance and 
do not qualify for medicaid a cancer diagnosis usually comes when 
the disease has advanced to a stage where little can be done except 
control the pain said harold p freeman cancer society president 
the combination of cancer and poverty is indeed a lethal 
combination said freeman chief of surgery at harlem hospital in 
new york 
the chance of getting cancer and dying from it is 
disproportionately higher among poor americans regardless of 
race freeman said in introducing a report based on hearings the 
society held along with the national cancer institute and the 
centers for disease control in may and june 
he called for a new kind of war on cancer a guerrilla war to 
break the economic and cultural barriers that prevent the poor from 
getting early cancer diagnoses and adequate treatment for the 
disease 
the cancer society says that in general half of all cancer 
patients are expected to live for at least five years after 
diagnosis however only 35 percent to 40 percent of cancer patients 
who live below the poverty level can expect the same the society 
says 
the society estimates that 178000 people with cancer who might 
have been saved through early diagnosis and treatment will die this 
year freeman estimated that half or more of them are poor 
the cancer societys regional hearings found that the poor must 
make extraordinary sacrifices to pay for health care and that these 
americans find the healthcare system insensitive and intimidating 
cassandra middleton a 26yearold cancer victim from johns 
island sc who testified at one of the hearings and joined cancer 
society officials at mondays news conference summed up her 
experience with the medical community they made me feel poor i 
know i am but they made me feel it too 
middleton described the bureaucratic maze she had to navigate to 
become eligible for medicaid and other public health assistance 
only about 45 percent of those living below the poverty level are 
eligible for medicaid 
for most of the people who have slipped through the holes of the 
social safety net the hospital emergency room becomes their entry 
to the health care system but suspicion of cancer even a lump in 
the breast does not qualify as a medical emergency and poor 
patients with symptoms but not in a lifethreatening crisis 
generally are not treated freeman said 
one of the key problems he said is that cancer prevention 
efforts have failed to reach poor americans because the education 
programs are unrealistic they are not relevant and they are not 
spoken in the language of the people they are trying to reach 
the result is a belief among the poor and uneducated that a 
diagnosis of cancer is a silent death sentence freeman said 
there is a pervasive sense of fatalism in the poor and this leads 
to an overall feeling of powerlessness 
the cancer society presented the report as a national call to 
action and gave it to president bush congressional leaders and 
health and human services secretary louis sullivan 
for its part the cancer society said it is committing 18 
million for national demonstration programs in harlem miami and 
oakland calif to develop cancer education and detection programs 
for the poor the group recently allocated an additional 1 million 
to support local education and research activities targeted to the 
poor nationwide 
freeman said the society has made no policy recommendations to 
congress or the bush administration but he said the american 
healthcare system has to be relooked at the society may make 
specific recommendations after its national board meets in november 
he said 
