scientists are working on a safetoeat nearly 
invisible coating made from milk that could extend the shelf life of 
fruit and vegetables the agriculture department said monday 
attila e pavlath a chemist with the departments agricultural 
research service said tests are concentrating on a film based on 
casein a milk protein a small amount of vitamin c is added to help 
protect against browning 
pavlath who works at the agencys research laboratory in albany 
calif said in a report released here that small pieces of sliced 
and peeled apple dipped in the coating stayed fresh for several 
days unprotected pieces shriveled and turned brown within a few 
hours 
the scientists want to make the film thinner a process that 
might take two more years pavlath said 
films that the tongue cannot feel and the taste buds cannot 
detect also could be made from protein in soybeans corn and 
wheat the report said 
some people who like fresh produce dont necessarily want to 
spend time in their kitchen washing slicing peeling pitting and 
paring pavlath said its part of the trend toward buying food 
that is ready to use and easy to store 
a successful coating would allow more types of produce to be 
presliced and packaged such coatings may have other potential 
uses perhaps for keeping fillings in pizzas or preventing pies from 
soaking the crust 
unlike waxes on cucumbers or other edible coatings such as the 
skin on sausages new films could be modified to add flavors or 
colors to standard fare pavlath said 
one possibility he said would be fresh sliced pears protected 
with a somewhat thicker protein coating flavored with red cherries 
