<TEXT>
a 60 million star wars experiment was praised 
by its managers monday as a major achievement in advancing plans 
for a spacebased missile shield but they said congressional budget 
cuts raise questions about the systems future 
the experiment launched over white sands missile range in new 
mexico on thursday tested how a neutral particle beam accelerator 
would work in space it was the first time such a beam of atomic 
particles was fired into the heavens 
the test known as bear or beam experiment aboard rocket was 
considered a primary step in pentagons research into the lasers 
beam accelerators and other futuristic weapons which would be 
designed to shoot down nuclear missiles fired at the united states 
or its allies 
the strategic defense initiative as star wars is formally 
called would make use of particle beams as a potential antimissile 
weapon a beam would determine whether an object is a decoy or an 
enemy warhead and could be used to disable a missile 
last weeks experiment involved lifting into space just for a 
few minutes a neutral particle beam accelerator atop a small aires 
rocket before the rocket returned to earth the accelerator was 
turned on and scientists collected data on how it worked and how the 
particle beams moved 
at a news conference monday the experiments managers declared 
the test a success displaying a fuzzy black and white video tape of 
the bright pulsing beam as it emerged from the rocket 
air force col thomas meyer head of the sdi organizations 
office of directed energy said the experiment showed that the 
complex equipment needed to produce the beam could be made in a 
compact way survive being shot into space and function well 
it is a major achievement both in technology and 
engineering meyer said 
he said the experiment demonstrates the promise of sdi that 
we have talked about all along 
in the laboratory the equipment used for ground experiments of 
the system would fill an averagesize house while the payload 
aboard the rocket was about 24 feet in length and 3 feet in 
diameter 
the director said the programs designers and scientists also 
wanted to test how the beam acted in space and how space affected it 
all experiment objectives were succesfully achieved he 
said 
meyer asked how long it will take before the system could become 
a fullfledged weapon in space indicated that budget cuts are more 
of a problem than technical difficulties 
the real issue is what is the funding for sdi meyer said 
its difficult for me to tell you when well have a weapon in 
space without a clear definition of what our future funding is and 
its continuing to be up in the air 
on capitol hill rep les aspin chairman of the house armed 
services committee said a number of programs have yet to go in 
terms of proving and particle beams is one 
i have not seen the briefing my reaction is skepticism to say 
that its all fixed he added 
meyer called the elements of last weeks experiment 
ontheshelf hardware but that some engineering problems still 
need to be worked out 
it only takes the money to put it together and thats when 
well get the weapon he said 
army lt col warren higgins a former manager of the bear 
program also at the briefing disputed the notion that the tests 
were in conflict with the 1972 antiballistic missile treaty 
critics of the star wars program say the treaty puts severe 
limits on testing and deployment of a spacebased defense 
we have a nonlethal beam we had no target higgins said 
adding that the experiments have been cleared as 
treatycompliant 
defense secretary dick cheney has battled congressional budget 
cuts in the spacebased antimissile defense 
the house armed services committee has approved a 35 billion 
budget for sdi compared with the 46 billion president bush 
proposed the senate armed services committee reduced the 
administrations request to 45 billion 
</TEXT>
