a sixmember jury was chosen monday in us 
district court to hear a lawsuit accusing korean air lines of 
willful misconduct when one of its passenger jets was shot down by 
soviet planes in 1983 klling all 269 people aboard 
families of 132 of the passengers killed when flight 007 was 
destroyed are suing kal alleging that the planes crew due to a 
navigational mistake deliberately left uncorrected allowed the 
plane to go hundreds of miles off course over a period of several 
hours into soviet air space 
after the six jurors and three alternates were chosen and sent 
home for the day lawyers for the airline asked judge aubrey 
robinson to limit presentation of the conclusions of a report on the 
shootdown by the international civil aviation organization 
the icao said flight 007 had been off course for nearly 5 hours 
before it was destroyed 
robinson said any analysis in the report which the families want 
to present in court must be found to have a reasonable basis 
before he will admit it into evidence 
but the judge said he had no intention of keeping most of the 
information in the report out of the case 
i do not see the report as being wholly untenable the judge 
told kal attorneys 
the case will turn on whether plaintiffs can show willful 
misconduct by the crew failing that international agreements limit 
them to recovering at most 75000 each 
lawyers for the families have contended that crew members chose 
to continue the flight with a flawed program in the aircraft 
navigation system rather than return to the starting point to 
reprogram it possibly leaving them open to company discipline 
previously the judge said a failure to notice that the flight 
was offcourse at point a or point b or point c might be 
evidence only of negligence but a failure to notice that the 
flight was offcourse at point a and point b and point c is 
susceptible to a different interpretation 
the trial could last three to four weeks the judge told jurors 
