cut to finance any program including catastrophicillness insurance 
for older americans 
rep dan rostenkowski dill made the statement to reporters 
after his committee again failed to change the insurance program 
whose financing mechanism is under heavy fire from retirees 
there apparently is no majority in the committee for any of 
several ideas for changing the incometax surcharge paid only by 
higherincome older citizens or the flat monthly premium paid by all 
but the poorest beneficiaries 
the most popular idea appears to be to let the program continue 
as is said rep james moody dwis 
the committee meeting ended in disagreement with rostenkowski 
saying he would put together a package to include catastrophic 
insurance extending several expiring provisions and miscellaneous 
tax provisions including ways to pay for them 
but the package wont include president bushs proposal to cut 
the capitalgains tax as a way to raise revenue when asked why 
rostenkowski replied because im a democrat 
democrats generally oppose a cut in the capitalgains tax which 
applies to profits from stocks and other investments because almost 
all the benefit would flow to those with annual incomes over 
100000 
bush and his advisers insist that a capitalgains cut would 
actually increase government revenues by generating new economic 
activity democrats generally argue that although a reduction would 
bring in more revenue in the first year it would lose money in 
later years 
although the capitalgains reduction is a prime topic of 
conversation by washington lobbyists lawmakers apparently are 
getting far more mail about the catastrophic insurance enacted a 
year ago the program was designed to protect medicare recipients 
from catastrophic costs of a major illness 
twothirds of the cost is paid by upperincome people 65 and 
older along with their federal income tax in 1989 the surtax can 
be up to 800 per beneficiary to pay that full amount a single 
person would have to have total income above about 42000 almost 
59 percent of retirees would pay no surtax 
the remaining part of the cost is paid by most recipients through 
the premium they already pay for part b medicare which covers 
doctors bills for 1989 the regular part b premium is 2790 plus 
4 for catastrophic coverage 
higherincome retirees subject to the surtax contend society in 
general should pay for the benefits for those retirees whose incomes 
are so low they escape most of the cost 
this is a totallose situation said committee member rep 
brian donnelly dmass who suggested the panel may have to leave 
the decision up to the house 
