<TEXT>
following is a chronology of events in 
nicaragua since the leftwing sandinistas came to power in 1979 
after leading the civil war that ousted president anastasio somoza 
july 17 1979 somoza whose family had ruled nicaragua with 
us support since the 1930s flees to miami 
july 19 1979 victorious sandinista guerrillas enter managua 
and begin their rule 
november 1980 first attacks launched by antisandinista rebels 
known as contras the name coming from a contraction of the spanish 
word for counterrevolutionaries 
february 1981 reagan administration announces suspension of aid 
to nicaragua and accuses nicaragua of supporting leftist guerrillas 
in el salvador 
july 8 1981 eden pastora known as commander zero defects 
from the sandinista government and becomes a leader of nicaragua 
rebels 
november 1982 reports emerge alleging covert us aid to the 
contras 
may 1 1983 nicaragua claims violations of its territory by 
us spy planes and warships 
april 67 1984 commando units operating from a us ship plant 
mines in nicaraguas ports 
april 9 1984 nicaragua asks the international court of justice 
to order the united states to cease aiding the contras the reagan 
administration had announced it would not accept the courts 
jurisdiction 
jan 10 1985 daniel ortega is inaugurated as president 
following national elections 
march 20 1985 the us house of representatives defeats 
president ronald reagans proposal for 100 million in military and 
humanitarian aid to the contras but later reverses itself and passes 
the package on june 25 
may 1 1985 reagan announces a trade embargo against nicaragua 
june 27 1985 the international court of justice says us 
support for the contras is a violation of the un charters ban on 
use of force 
aug 13 1985 the us senate approves reagans 100 million 
aid package 
oct 5 1986 an americanmanned cargo plane is shot down in 
southern nicaragua the surviving crew member eugene hasenfus is 
captured and implicates the cia in the contrasupply operation 
hasenfus subsequently is freed 
nov 25 1986 attorney general edwin meese iii discloses that 
some of the profits from the sale of american arms to iran had been 
secretly diverted to the contras in an operation run by marine lt 
col oliver north 
aug 7 1987 five central american presidents sign a peace plan 
sponsored by costa rican president oscar arias it includes 
amnesties for political prisoners democratic reforms an end to 
foreign aid for rebel forces and a prohibition against one country 
allowing guerrillas to use its territory to attack another 
jan 19 1988 nicaragua lifts a 6yearold state of emergency 
feb 3 1988 the us congress cuts off arms aid to the contras 
but continues nonmilitary aid 
mar 21 1988 the sandinistas and contras meet facetoface for 
the first time in nicaraguan territory 
april 1 1988 a formal truce begins 
may 31 1988 the sandinistas extend truce on a monthly basis 
a practice they have continued the contras say they consider the 
truce indefinite talks break off but fighting declines 
july 11 1988 us ambassador richard melton is expelled with 
the government accusing him of inciting destabilization washington 
expels carlos tunnerman nicaraguas envoy to the united states 
jan 30 1989 ortega announces a harsh austerity program to 
combat inflation that surpasses 20000 percent annually 
feb 14 1989 five central american countries sign an accord at 
a summit in el salvador ortega promises early elections in exchange 
for dismantling of the contras based in honduran jungle camps 
april 18 1989 president bush signs a 49 million measure that 
continues nonlethal aid to the contras 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

