<TEXT>
the house voted monday to reduce the interior 
secretarys authority over the national parks in what supporters of 
the bill said was an effort to keep politics out of the 
environmental decisions 
rep bruce vento dminn said the bill also was designed to 
protect professional park employees who he said are being harassed 
and intimidated by political appointees 
republican opponents of the bill which was approved by voice 
vote said it would be vetoed by president bush it still must go 
through the senate before reaching the presidents desk 
a similar measure passed last year by the house was never acted 
on by the senate 
the issue is to let the professionals use professional 
judgments said vento who led debate in favor the bill 
but rep john rhodes rariz who opposed the measure said it 
was bad law that removes the park service control from one group 
of political appointees by just putting it under control of 
another set of political operatives 
the legislation would require the president to nominate a park 
service director who would be confirmed by the senate for a 
fiveyear term and be answerable directly to congress 
the interior secretary would relinquish almost all power over the 
parks including hiring to the director the secretary would still 
have to approve the budget of the national park service before 
submission to the president 
currently the director of the national park service is appointed 
by the interior secretary without senate confirmation and may be 
removed by the secretary 
with one exception in the late 1960s park service directors have 
always been professional park managers either from the federal 
system or a state system 
an amendment offered by rhodes that would have eliminated all 
provisions of the bill except the one requiring the director to be 
confirmed by the senate failed 148251 
vento said if the final vote on passage had been by roll call 
there would have been a twothirds majority the margin needed to 
overturn a presidential veto 
vento said however the fight in the senate for the measure 
would be tougher 
environmentalists clashed several times with the reagan 
administration over its supervision of the parks and alleged 
dictation of national park service decisions 
as land and resource scarcity has increased so have the 
pressures of certain segments of society to take actions detrimental 
to the basic legislative directives to protect the national park 
system said the report from the interior committee which handled 
hearings on the bill 
such actions have polarized opposite reactions from citizen 
groups and the general public who see park resources being seriously 
degraded 
the report said professional resource managers decisionmaking 
has been supplanted by political decisionmaking 
