<TEXT>
president bush is being advised to veto any 
legislation which forbids him to use money from other countries for 
activities denied funds by congress such as helping the contra 
rebels sen jesse helms said monday 
this doesnt even make good nonsense because congress doesnt 
have the authority to do that said helms rnc as debate 
opened on an amendment offered by sen daniel patrick moynihan 
dny to a pending state department authorization bill 
it is a direct explicit and conscious attack on the separation 
of powers helms said of the amendment on which the senate will 
vote tuesday 
it is nothing less than an attempt by congress to criminalize 
foreign policy 
i get the impression in the political climate in washington 
today that there is an effort to milk that irancontra cow that goes 
on and on and on helms said 
the moynihan amendment springs from disclosures at the 
congressional irancontra hearings that the reagan administration 
solicited funds from foreign nations to aid the contra rebels in 
nicaragua at a time when congress had barred using us funds to 
provide such aid 
during the hearings the countries were referred to by code names 
such as country one and country two and the like but it was 
clear that nations like saudi arabia and brunei had contributed 
former marine lt col oliver l north then a staff member of 
the national security council was described in testimony as having 
been heavily engaged in such solicitation 
the moynihan amendment would make what north and others did 
illegal 
the amendment would provide penalties of up to five years in jail 
for any officer or employee of the government who solicits funds or 
material aid for a prohibited activity from any foreign government 
foreign national or us citizen 
the amendment also would cut off us foreign aid to another 
nation if that would have the effect of assisting the activity 
proscribed by congress 
undersecretary of state lawrence eagleburger in a letter read by 
helms said the amendment would seriously affect the ability of bush 
or any succeeding president from conducting foreign policy 
he said that if congress attaches the moynihan amendment to the 
state department authorization bill we would recommend the 
president disapprove the bill 
moynihan said there is no question about this legislation 
being necessary we went through an extensive painful and divisive 
inquiry into practices in the executive branch which clearly 
undermined the will of congress but took place even so 
helms contended that while congress can bar spending tax dollars 
on an executive branch policy it cannot under the constitution bar 
the administration from finding the money elsewhere 
he argued that the president has the power to do that as he sees 
fit and can only be punished for such action by impeachment or 
defeat at the polls not by criminal sanctions 
but moynihan said congress has the right to act to prevent the 
laws it passes from being circumvented 
this is not just our right it is our responsibility he 
said were trying to protect the presidency and the process 
