the rev martin alphonse a methodist minister from madras 
india said at the lausanne ii conference that such dialogue will 
not be seen as a threat to or an open assault on other faiths 
by playing a low key it will still be able to permeate the 
various spheres of peoples of other faiths in a quiet but firm 
way said alphonse who lives in a predominantly hindu city 
the conference which opened last tuesday has brought together 
about 4200 evangelical christians from more than 160 countries to 
devise ways to spread the christian religion worldwide by the end of 
the century 
alphonse told the delegates that they face a seemingly 
insurmountable task in reaching 900 million moslems 690 million 
hindus 320 million buddhists and others by the year 2000 
we are not thinking about organized conventions and 
evangelistic crusades for thousands of them exclusively in one 
place he said such strategy may not simply work 
rather we are thinking about world evangelization by local 
evangelization by reaching a few here and a few there thus 
eventually making this gospel proliferate everywhere he said 
colin chapman a lecturer in religion at trinity university in 
bristol england said such quiet dialogue paralleled the style of 
preaching used by jesus and the apostles when dealing with jews and 
members of other religions in the roman empire 
