<TEXT>
its summer and americans are on the road 
enjoying new places and burglars are out searching for the vacant 
houses left behind 
for many people the perception of a burglar is someone breaking 
into a home in the dark of night but that isnt always the case 
the fbi reports 
more home burglaries occur in the daytime than at night and in 
nearly onefourth of the cases the crook simply gets in through an 
unlocked door or window the fbi has found 
many cases are simply crimes of opportunity with people knocking 
on doors and if there is no answer trying the door if it opens 
they go in and help themselves police explain if the door is 
locked they go on to the next house 
that means a simple thing like making sure the door is kept 
locked can prevent a burglary certainly a costeffective measure if 
ever there was one 
of course that means all doors not just the front door make 
sure there are locks on windows and attic basement and garage 
doors too 
if you are unsure about where your home may be vulverable check 
your local police department many departments will conduct free or 
lowcost home security audits and make suggestions for improvement 
one of the things they stress is to never leave keys available 
outside the home 
once upon a time people left keys in mailboxes or under doormats 
with little fear but no more today thieves know all the obvious 
places to look and check them out quickly 
the insurance information institute which is interested in crime 
because its members wind up paying for many of the losses suggests 
making the home look livedin while you are away 
for example ask neighbors to collect mail and newspapers and 
have someone mow the lawn 
in addition get automatic timers for the lights and set them to 
turn lights on and off in different rooms at different times to make 
it look like someone is home 
a telephone answering machine can be a good idea too that way 
thieves arent tipped off by an unanswered ringing phone turn off 
automatic garage door openers while away 
the insurance group urges putting ladders away and says to be 
sure not to advertise your vacation in the newspaper society columns 
valuables should be locked in a safe or safety deposit box the 
costly items should be inventoried with photos for use in making 
insurance claims and identifying the items in the event of theft 
electronic equipment is among the most popular with crooks so 
make a mark on it to identify it later for example many people 
engrave their social security number on a metal part of the product 
electric engraving tools can be rented or borrowed from many police 
departments or purchased at a reasonable price 
finally when coming home from vacation check the house before 
going in if there is any sign of entry go to a neighbors house 
and call the police the last thing you want to do is walk in on a 
burglar in the act 
