<TEXT>
the philadelphia and american stock exchanges are 
discussing either a full or partial merger the new york times 
reported in tuesdays editions 
under the plans which are in the preliminary stages either the 
exchanges would be combined outright or they would merge their 
optionstrading operations the newspaper reported quoting 
unidentified sources 
the merger discussions are fueled by a recent rule adopted by the 
securities and exchange commission regarding the trading of equity 
options the sources said 
under the rule which will be phased in over the next few years 
multiple exchanges would be able to trade an equity option unlike 
the current system in which each option is allotted exclusively to 
an exchange 
the largest market for options currently is the chicago board of 
options 
an option is a right to buy or sell a block of stock at a certain 
price within a stipulated time 
the times said its sources told it that the philadelphia exchange 
was growing increasingly worried that the rule would take away its 
options business since in competition with other exchanges the 
philadelphia exchange would likely be in the weakest position 
because its market share is smaller than the american exchange and 
the chicago board of options 
a full merger of the two exchages would be the first in this 
country in decades industry officials said under that plan the 
philadelphia exchange would be operated as a branch of the american 
exchange which is based in new york the times sources said 
negotiations on the possible merger have been going on for about 
a month the times said 
</TEXT>
